post_cb({"26221962": {"ParentId": "26221911", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>From N3485 \u00a712.1 [class.ctor]/5:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_26221911_26221962_0\">If there is no user-declared constructor for class X, a constructor having no parameters is implicitly declared as defaulted (8.4).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><code>Foo(Foo const &amp;) = delete;</code> is a user-declared constructor, so no default constructor is generated by the compiler.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "962089", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "26221962", "Score": "10", "CreationDate": "2014-10-06T17:55:23.197", "LastActivityDate": "2014-10-06T17:55:23.197"}, "26221911": {"CommentCount": "0", "ViewCount": "137", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "2684539", "CreationDate": "2014-10-06T17:52:30.250", "LastActivityDate": "2014-10-06T18:01:14.520", "Title": "Where in the C++ standard does it state that the default constructor is not generated when the copy constructor is deleted?", "AcceptedAnswerId": "26221962", "LastEditDate": "2014-10-06T18:01:14.520", "Id": "26221911", "Score": "4", "Body": "<p>The C++11 program</p>\n<pre><code>struct Foo {\n    Foo(Foo const &amp;) = delete;\n};\n\nint main() {\n    Foo foo;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>generates the error</p>\n<pre><code>$ g++ -std=c++11 junk.cpp -o junk\njunk.cpp: In function 'int main()':\njunk.cpp:6:9: error: no matching function for call to 'Foo::Foo()'\njunk.cpp:6:9: note: candidate is:\njunk.cpp:2:5: note: Foo::Foo(const Foo&amp;) &lt;deleted&gt;\njunk.cpp:2:5: note:   candidate expects 1 argument, 0 provided\n</code></pre>\n<p>Now, it looks like the default constructor was prevented from being generated because the copy constructor was deleted.  I'm going to assume this is the expected behavior, but where in the C++ standard does it specify that the default constructor should not be generated when the copy constructor is deleted?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><c++11><constructor><language-lawyer>", "OwnerUserId": "1932452", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_26221911_26221962_0": {"section_id": 369, "quality": 1.0, "length": 10}}, "n3337": {"so_26221911_26221962_0": {"section_id": 359, "quality": 1.0, "length": 10}}, "n4659": {"so_26221911_26221962_0": {"section_id": 381, "quality": 1.0, "length": 10}}}});